    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="la">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName ref="#sauma"><expan><abbr>Fl</abbr><ex>avius</ex></expan> <choice><reg>Saumae</reg><orig>Saume</orig></choice></persName> <choice><reg>biarcho</reg><orig>biarco</orig></choice> de numero <w xml:id="w1">e<choice><corr>q</corr><sic>o</sic></choice>ui<choice><corr>t</corr><sic>i</sic></choice>um</w> <w xml:id="w2">Bracchia<choice><corr>t</corr><sic>i</sic></choice>orum</w>.
                    <lb n="2"/>Arcam illi <w xml:id="w3">emerun<choice><corr>i</corr><sic>t</sic></choice></w>: frater <persName ref="#viax">Viax</persName> et <persName ref="#evingus">Evingus</persName>, se<choice><corr>n</corr><sic>m</sic></choice><supplied reason="omitted">a</supplied>tor, <persName ref="#alagildus"><w xml:id="w4">Ala</w></persName>
                    <lb n="3" break="no"/><persName ref="#alagildus"><w xml:id="w5"><choice><corr>g</corr><sic>c</sic></choice>ildus</w></persName>, <choice><reg>biarchus</reg><orig>biarcus</orig></choice>. Si <w xml:id="w6"><choice><corr>q</corr><sic>o</sic></choice>uis</w> illam aperire voluerit, dabit fisco auri
                    <lb n="4"/><measure type="fine" unit="roman_pound" commodity="gold" quantity="1">libram unam</measure>.
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app loc="1" from="#w1" to="w1">
                        <lem>e<choice><corr>q</corr><sic>o</sic></choice>ui<choice><corr>t</corr><sic>i</sic></choice>um</lem>
                        <rdg source="#bertolini1875a">eouium</rdg>
                        <rdg source="#bertolini1876b #cilv8760 #ils2804 #ilcv493 #edr097908">equitum</rdg>
                        <rdg source="#lettich1983">equi<choice><corr>t</corr><sic>i</sic></choice>um</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="1" from="#w2" to="w2">
                        <lem>Bracchia<choice><corr>t</corr><sic>i</sic></choice>orum</lem>
                        <rdg source="#bertolini1875a #bertolini1876b">Bracchiatorum</rdg>
                        <rdg source="#cilv8760 #ils2804 #ilcv493 #edr097908"><expan><abbr>Bracchiatoru</abbr><ex>m</ex></expan></rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2" from="#w3" to="w3">
                        <lem>emerun<choice><corr>i</corr><sic>t</sic></choice></lem>
                        <rdg source="#bertolini1875a #bertolini1876b #cilv8760 #ils2804 #ilcv493 #edr097908">emerunt</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2-3" from="#w4" to="w5">
                        <lem>Ala<lb n="3" break="no"/><choice><corr>g</corr><sic>c</sic></choice>ildus</lem>
                        <rdg source="#bertolini1875a #bertolini1876b #cilv8760 #ils2804 #ilcv493 #edr097908">Ala<lb n="3" break="no"/>gildus</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="3" from="#w6" to="w6">
                        <lem><choice><corr>q</corr><sic>o</sic></choice>uis</lem>
                        <rdg source="#bertolini1875a #bertolini1876b #cilv8760 #ils2804 #ilcv493 #edr097908">quis</rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>
                    To <persName ref="#sauma" xml:lang="la">Flavius Sauma</persName>, <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> of the <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term> of the <term xml:lang="la">Equites Bracchiati</term>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    They purchased the sarcophagus for him: his brother <persName ref="#viax" xml:lang="la">Viax</persName>, the <term xml:lang="la">senator</term> <persName ref="#evingus" xml:lang="la">Evingus</persName>, and the <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> <persName ref="#alagildus" xml:lang="la">Alagildus</persName>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    If anyone should wish to open it, he shall pay one (Roman) pound of gold to the <term xml:lang="la">fiscus</term>.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p>
                    A Flavio Sauma, <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> del <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term> degli <term xml:lang="la">Equites Bracchiati</term>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Comprarono l'arca per costui: il fratello Viax, il <term xml:lang="la">senator</term> Evingo e il <term xml:lang="la">biarchus</term> Alagildo.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Se qualcuno vorrà aprirlo, verserà al <term xml:lang="la">fiscus</term> una libbra (romana) d'oro.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>
                    Sauma was a <term ref="#biarchus" xml:lang="la">biarchus</term>, a cavalryman of the <term xml:lang="la">equites Bracchiati seniores</term>, a <term>vexilatio palatina</term> which, according to the <term xml:lang="la">Notitia Dignitatum</term>, was stationed in Italy (<term xml:lang="la">ND occ</term>. 6, 45; 7, 161). 
                </p>
                <p>
                    The brother of <persName ref="#sauma" xml:lang="la">Sauma</persName>, <persName ref="#viax" xml:lang="la">Viax</persName>, and the deceased's colleagues, <persName ref="#evingus" xml:lang="la">Evingus</persName> and <persName ref="#alagildus" xml:lang="la">Alagildus</persName>, dedicated the burial to him.
                </p>
                <p>
                    While the origin of the names <persName xml:lang="la">Evingus</persName> and <persName xml:lang="la">Alagildus</persName> is clearly Germanic (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#hoffmann1970">Hoffmann 1970, 32, nt. 274</ref>; <ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#lettich1983">Lettich 1983, 67</ref>), that of <persName xml:lang="la">Sauma</persName> and <persName xml:lang="la">Viax</persName> is more debated. According to Holder, Sauma is a name of Celtic origin (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#holder">Holder 1904, 1382</ref>); according to Hoffmann, it derives from the Greek σάγμα (cloak) (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#hoffmann1970">Hoffmann 1970, 32, nt. 275</ref>); according to Schönfeld, Sauma is a variant of Siuma, a Germanic name (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#schoenfeld">Schönfeld 1911, 282</ref>). Furthermore, according to Schönfeld, the cognomen <persName xml:lang="la">Viax</persName> is Germanic and derives from *Viha-ax (battle-axe) (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#schoenfeld">Schönfeld 1911, 262</ref>). In this critical edition, a Germanic origin for both names is considered more probable, as they are associated with other <term xml:lang="la">cognomina</term> of Germanic origin (<persName xml:lang="la">Evingus</persName> and <persName xml:lang="la">Alagildus</persName>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    The identity of <persName ref="#viax" xml:lang="la">Viax</persName> remains unclear. His military rank is not specified, but it would be unlikely for a civilian to follow his brother during the movements of his <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term>. It cannot be excluded that Viax was not in Concordia, but had simply contributed financially to Sauma's sarcophagus, sending a contribution to his colleagues. However, it is considered more likely that he was a soldier, a colleague of his brother and a member of the same <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term>, and that his rank was omitted as he was a common soldier. Similarly, it is probable that the <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term> of <persName ref="#evingus" xml:lang="la">Evingus</persName> and <persName ref="#alagildus" xml:lang="la">Alagildus</persName> is not mentioned because it would be implied and corresponding to that of <persName ref="#sauma" xml:lang="la">Sauma</persName>.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="it">
                <p>
                    Sauma era un <term ref="#biarchus" xml:lang="la">biarchus</term>, cavaliere degli <term xml:lang="la">equites Bracchiati seniores</term>, una <term>vexilatio palatina</term> che dalla <term xml:lang="la">Notitia Dignitatum</term> risulta stanziata in Italia (<term xml:lang="la">ND occ</term>. 6, 45; 7, 161). 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Il fratello di <persName ref="#sauma" xml:lang="la">Sauma</persName>, <persName ref="#viax" xml:lang="la">Viax</persName>, e i colleghi del defunto, <persName ref="#evingus" xml:lang="la">Evingus</persName> e <persName ref="#alagildus" xml:lang="la">Alagildus</persName>, gli dedicano la sepoltura.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Mentre l'origine dei nomi <persName xml:lang="la">Evingus</persName> e <persName xml:lang="la">Alagildus</persName> è chiaramente germanica (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#hoffmann1970">Hoffmann 1970, 32, nt. 274</ref>; <ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#lettich1983">Lettich 1983, 67</ref>), quella di <persName xml:lang="la">Sauma</persName> e <persName xml:lang="la">Viax</persName> è più dibattuta. Secondo Holder, Sauma è un nome di origine celtica (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#holder">Holder 1904, 1382</ref>); secondo Hoffmann, deriverebbe dal greco σάγμα (mantello) (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#hoffmann1970">Hoffmann 1970, 32, nt. 275</ref>); secondo Schönfeld, Sauma sarebbe una variante di Siuma, nome germanico (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#schoenfeld">Schönfeld 1911, 282</ref>). Sempre secondo Schönfeld, il cognomen <persName xml:lang="la">Viax</persName> sarebbe germanico e deriverebbe da *Viha-ax (ascia da battaglia) (<ref target="../references/bibliography.xml#schoenfeld">Schönfeld 1911, 262</ref>). In questa edizione critica, si ritiene più probabile l'origine germanica dei due nomi, dal momento che sono accostati ad altri <term xml:lang="la">cognomina</term> di origine germanica (<persName xml:lang="la">Evingus</persName> e <persName xml:lang="la">Alagildus</persName>).
                </p>
                <p>
                    L'identità di <persName ref="#viax" xml:lang="la">Viax</persName> non risulta chiara. Non viene specificato il suo grado militare, ma risulterebbe poco probabile che un civile seguisse il fratello negli spostamenti del suo <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term>. Non si può escludere che Viax non fosse a Concordia, ma avesse semplicemente contribuito economicamente all'arca di Sauma, inviando un contributo ai suoi colleghi. Tuttavia, si ritiene più probabile che fosse un soldato, collega del fratello e membro dello stesso <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term>, e che il rango fosse stato omesso in quanto soldato semplice. Analogamente, si ritiene probabile che il <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term> di <persName ref="#evingus" xml:lang="la">Evingus</persName> e <persName ref="#alagildus" xml:lang="la">Alagildus</persName> non sia menzionato perché sarebbe sottinteso e corrispondente a quello di <persName ref="#sauma" xml:lang="la">Sauma</persName>.
                </p>
            </div>
